node.text: The #coriander plant (Coriandrum sativum) produces both #cilantro and coriander. Cilantro is the herb made from leaves of the plant, and coriander is the spice made from its seeds. Part of the parsley family, coriander is one of the world’s longest-used culinary spices, dating back to 5,000 BC.

node.text: I love the nutty flavor of nutritional yeast and find myself sprinkling it on many savory dishes to punch up the taste. I often experiment with this versatile ingredient in many sauces and recipes. It is a deactivated yeast that is sold as a food product and it usually comes in the form of flakes or powder. It has a strong, savory #umami flavor that is variously described as cheesy, nutty and tangy.

Desert evening primrose blooming in my garden. 

Evening primrose oil comes from the seeds of another variety of this plant (Oenothera biennis). Indigenous Americans used evening primrose oil, seeds, leaves and roots for food. They also made poultices from the whole plant to heal bruises, and decoctions of the roots to treat hemorrhoids. The leaves were employed to treat minor wounds, gastrointestinal complaints, and sore throats. 

As we age, our bodies get drier inside and out. Evening primrose oil (EPO) nourishes the skin, hair, nails, even the joints. The gamma linolenic acid it contains helps strengthen the skin barrier and reduces moisture loss. EPO has anti-inflammatory effects without the side effects of anti-inflammatory drugs. I recommend it for arthritis, autoimmune disorders, premenstrual syndrome and for healthy growth of skin, hair, and nails. #eveningprimrose #eveningprimroseoil

Beautiful #beets harvested from my garden this morning. A tasty addition to any meal, beets are a good source of folate, manganese, potassium, fiber and vitamin C - nutrients that can help protect against heart disease, birth defects, and certain cancers.

While these root vegetables are known for their purple-red color, beets come in other hues, including white and golden-yellow. The sweet, earthy flavor is wonderful in salads, oven-roasted with a little olive oil, part of a cheese plate, or pureed in a cool, summer soup. When preparing red beets, don’t peel them until after cooking - leaving the skin in place will help them to retain their color and discourage the staining that often comes with these deep red gems!
